6 recovery.
7 D. As used in this section, "natural disaster"
8 means a disaster brought on by natural forces, such as a
9 drought, a fire, a flood, severe weather or an earthquake,
10 that threatens the public peace, health and safety or the
11 lives or property of the people of the state."
12 SECTION 6. Section 6-4-4 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1987,
13 Chapter 347, Section 4, as amended) is amended to read:
14 "6-4-4. TRANSFERS FROM THE GENERAL FUND.-- If the
15 revenues of the general fund exceed the total of
16 appropriations from the general fund, the excess revenue
17 shall be transferred to the general fund operating reserve;
18 provided that if the sum of the excess revenue plus the
19 balance in the general fund operating reserve prior to the
20 transfer is greater than eight percent of the aggregate
21 recurring appropriations from the general fund for the
22 previous fiscal year, then an amount equal to the smaller of
23 either the amount of the excess revenue or the difference
24 between the sum and eight percent of the aggregate recurring
25 appropriations from the general fund for the previous fiscal HAFC/HB 180/a
Page 10

1 year shall be transferred to the government results and
2 opportunity expendable trust."
3 SECTION 7. Section 20-1-6 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1987,
4 Chapter 318, Section 6, as amended) is amended to read:
5 "20-1-6. EXPENSES FOR TROOPS CALLED INTO SERVICE OF THE
6 STATE.--
7 A. All compensation of personnel and all the
8 necessary expenses incurred in quartering, housing, caring
9 for, subsisting, protecting, equipping, warning for duty and
10 transporting such officers and members and their equipment,
11 including the purchase or lease of any articles of material,
12 equipment or supplies reasonably required, designed or needed
13 to accomplish the purpose or results specified in the
14 governor's call for such troops into service of the state,
15 shall be paid by the state from the executive order for
16 disasters fund.
17 B. On or before the twentieth legislative day of
18 the next legislative session following the expenditures of
19 the sums provided for in this section, the governor shall
20 file a written report with the presiding officer of each
21 house of the legislature setting forth the purpose and the
22 amounts of money expended as provided in this section.
23 C. The provisions of this section may be used for
24 the operation of the national guard or the state defense
25 force when on militia duty." HAFC/HB 180/a
Page 11

1 SECTION 8. TEMPORARY PROVISION--DISASTER FUNDING TASK
2 FORCE.--The legislative finance committee shall convene a
3 disaster funding task force composed of the director of the
4 legislative finance committee, the state director of homeland
5 security and emergency management, the adjutant general of
6 the New Mexico national guard and the secretary of finance
7 and administration, or those individuals' designees. The
8 task force shall review the provisions of this act and make
9 recommendations for proposed legislation for the first
10 session of the fifty-eighth legislature. Members of the task
11 force shall report the recommendations to the legislative
12 finance committee by November 1, 2026. The report shall
13 identify issues related to fiscal controls, accountability,
14 transparency, contingency plans and disaster response
15 flexibility for the executive.
16 SECTION 9. TRANSFERS.--
17 A. The balance of the federal reimbursement
18 revolving fund is transferred to the executive order for
19 disasters fund.
20 B. The balance of the adjutant general emergency
21 public defense certificates fund is transferred to the
22 appropriation contingency fund.
23 SECTION 10. TRANSFERS TO NATURAL DISASTER REVOLVING
24 FUND.--Within thirty days after August 1 of 2026 and 2027,
25 the secretary of finance and administration shall calculate HAFC/HB 180/a
Page 12

1 the unexpended balance of the natural disaster revolving fund
2 and, subject to availability of funds, transfer from the
3 appropriation contingency fund to the natural disaster
4 revolving fund an amount not greater than fifty million
5 dollars ($50,000,000) less the balance of the natural
6 disaster revolving fund. If the unexpended balance of the
7 natural disaster revolving fund is equal to or greater than
8 fifty million dollars ($50,000,000), no transfer shall be
9 made.
10 SECTION 11. REPEAL.--Section 6-4-2.8 NMSA 1978 (being
11 Laws 2025, Chapter 157, Section 3) is repealed.
12 SECTION 12. DELAYED REPEAL.--Sections 12-11-23 through
13 12-11-25 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1955, Chapter 185, Sections 1
14 through 3, as amended) are repealed effective February 15,
15 2027.
16 SECTION 13. EFFECTIVE DATE--DELAYED EFFECTIVE DATE.--
17 A. The effective date of the provisions of
18 Sections 10 and 11 of this act is July 1, 2026.
19 B. The effective date of the provisions of
20 Sections 1 through 7 and 9 of this act is February 15, 2027. HAFC/HB 180/a
